But now please enjoy today's episode with Robin Hannell on participatory economics.

02:06.000 --> 02:16.000
So let's start with the more macro questions, because in the more recent work, you incorporate long term planning into the model of Paracom.

02:16.000 --> 02:25.000
And this also means that before the annual participatory planning procedure, before this begins, certain decisions have already been made.

02:25.000 --> 02:32.000
A participatory investment plan has determined the amount of each capital good that must be produced during the year.

02:33.000 --> 02:44.000
The second one would be a long run education and environmental plan that has determined the natural resource, the resources that can be used throughout the production cycle.

02:44.000 --> 02:56.000
And the third one would be, as you just mentioned, a strategic international economic plan that has determined the amounts of different goods that will be exported and imported during the year.

02:56.000 --> 03:06.000
And another macro question that has to be addressed in Paracom as well would be the question of reproductive labor.

03:06.000 --> 03:16.000
I imagine that it will be difficult that we already talked for a long time, so it will be difficult to address each of these sections in detail.

03:16.000 --> 03:26.000
But maybe you could give us an idea of how would Paracom try to address this, the special attention that those sectors need in each of these categories?

03:26.000 --> 03:36.000
Right, there's a lot to cover. And the first thing I'd like to say is that all of these issues are ones that we didn't talk about for a long, long time.

03:36.000 --> 03:46.000
For, I mean, the original publications of some of the idea of a participatory economy, that was 1990.

03:46.000 --> 03:56.000
And it really isn't until 2021, when democratic economic planning was published, that we tackled all these issues, at least in public.

03:56.000 --> 04:02.000
I mean, it's not like we hadn't been talking about them. We hadn't gone into print with proposals.

04:02.000 --> 04:14.000
And there was a reason for that. I mean, the reason for that was we thought, first, we have to sort of get straight about whether we're talking about a market socialist economy or some sort of central planning.

04:14.000 --> 04:26.000
Is there really an alternative? And in that context, talking about the annual planning procedure, as well as talking about some really important things that socialist, I mean,

04:26.000 --> 04:42.000
no practicing socialist economies had ever really put into practice, things like balancing for desirability, balancing for empowerment, and, of course, dealing with the age-old issue of what's a fair system of rewarding people.

04:42.000 --> 04:52.000
So we had talked about all those things, and we knew that that leaves a lot of decisions, sort of a lot of important subject areas, unaddressed.

04:52.000 --> 05:02.000
The reason it's important to say this before starting is everything that we're now going to talk about, I consider to be unvetted.

05:02.000 --> 05:12.000
This hasn't been discussed and argued and criticized for 10, 20, 30 years the way a bunch of other things have.

05:12.000 --> 05:24.000
So we've sort of had a more or less full debate out there in the literature, whereas these things, my own attitude toward them is, hey, we're just throwing these out here for the first time.

05:24.000 --> 05:36.000
I haven't heard people coming up with objections yet. I don't even know how I'm going to feel once I start hearing that.

05:36.000 --> 05:48.000
So in some sense, one of the implications of this is the first time we've actually put something out there is I honestly feel less secure and sure about it.

05:48.000 --> 05:54.000
I can't even promise you how much I will continue to defend it 10 years from now.

05:54.000 --> 06:08.000
So I wanted to say that just to begin with. There are some really important problems that you have to deal with when you're doing long-term planning over time that you don't have to deal with when you're doing the annual plan.

06:08.000 --> 06:18.000
When we do the annual plan, presumably workers councils know what their technological options are.

06:18.000 --> 06:29.000
They know what different technologies they currently have available to them, and presumably consumers have some idea of what their preferences are.

06:29.000 --> 06:42.000
So those are given, those things we know when we set up a system to do annual planning, but who knows what preferences of people are going to be 20 years from now?

06:42.000 --> 06:50.000
And who knows what technologies will become available? What new technologies will become available?

06:50.000 --> 07:00.000
But if you want to make an efficient plan about anything over 10 or 20 years, you have to actually know those things.

07:00.000 --> 07:11.000
So there's a whole bunch of things that that means that part of what will determine what is an efficient investment is what you're going to do.

07:12.000 --> 07:31.000
So there's a whole bunch of things that that means that part of what will determine what is an efficient investment plan or education plan or environmental plan, part of what will determine whether this plan is efficient or not is

07:31.000 --> 07:42.000
What sort of technological change has taken place over these will occur in the future? And if there are changes in people's preferences, what those will be like in the future?

07:42.000 --> 07:50.000
Somebody is going to have to estimate those. And when you estimate those, you're going to make mistakes.

07:50.000 --> 07:58.000
So these are all problems that long term planning, you know, face that annual planning does not face.

07:58.000 --> 08:09.000
And then there's another problem. If we want the planning process to be democratic, we would like everybody who's going to be affected by the plan to participate.

08:09.000 --> 08:13.000
Well, people who aren't born yet can't participate.

08:13.000 --> 08:26.000
So you have, if you set up a democratic process for coming up with long term plans, you have to address who's going to speak for the unborn generations.

08:26.000 --> 08:42.000
And so we started with this part of the reason that we delayed as long as we did, even coming up with proposals that we recognize that while the general principle that you want the decisions to be made in a participatory way,

08:42.000 --> 08:55.000
you want decisions to be self managed, you want the process to be fair, you want it to be efficient, the principles are all the same, but there's extra problems.

08:55.000 --> 09:07.000
And I think those are the things that are sort of important to get out there just right from the very beginning.

09:07.000 --> 09:22.000
So what we proposed is a procedure for going about what we simply call investment planning.

09:22.000 --> 09:37.000
When we think of investment planning, we're basically thinking of this year we could produce consumption goods, but this year we could also produce what are typically called capital goods or investment goods.

09:37.000 --> 09:43.000
Well, when we produce a capital good or an investment good this year, it doesn't do anybody this year any good at all.

09:43.000 --> 09:45.000
So why would you do that?

09:45.000 --> 09:55.000
Because if you produce capital or investment goods next year, you'll be able to produce more goods than you could this year.

09:55.000 --> 10:08.000
So investment planning is basically a decision about, and most capital goods or investment goods basically last for figure a decade.

10:08.000 --> 10:14.000
So what's the time length that makes sort of sense for investment planning?

10:14.000 --> 10:18.000
And the answer is sort of think in terms of a decade.

10:18.000 --> 10:24.000
So if we make a new machine this year, it's probably going to either be worn out or obsolete 10 years from now.

10:24.000 --> 10:33.000
That's why 10 year time period is sort of a sensible period for investment planning.

10:33.000 --> 10:37.000
Education planning, that's not the case.

10:37.000 --> 10:41.000
I mean, how long does it take to educate somebody?

10:41.000 --> 10:46.000
Well, 18 years gets you through high school.

10:46.000 --> 10:50.000
Another four and maybe two more for graduate school in some cases.

10:50.000 --> 10:56.000
And then we have a whole process of sort of lifetime learning that goes on.

10:56.000 --> 11:05.000
So if you're talking about education planning, used to be called manpower planning, by the way.

11:05.000 --> 11:07.000
But we can't do that anymore, thank heavens.

11:08.000 --> 11:18.000
But when you say education planning, when you use the word manpower planning, it was clear that you also didn't just consider the formal education system.

11:18.000 --> 11:32.000
You were also considering any sort of education and training procedures that worker councils were setting up for themselves.

11:32.000 --> 11:42.000
So at least the old term manpower planning, while sexist, at least focus people's attention on the fact that this is a combination of the formal education system.

11:42.000 --> 11:48.000
And inside the economy itself, we have an awful lot of education and training that goes on.

11:48.000 --> 11:55.000
So that's a process that's going to stretch over three or four decades, at least.

11:55.000 --> 12:03.000
And when you talk about environmental planning, we need to plan 50 to 100 years out.

12:03.000 --> 12:08.000
So the timeframes are quite different in these regards.

12:08.000 --> 12:12.000
So we've identified that there's very different timeframes.

12:12.000 --> 12:17.000
We've identified that we know what we're trying to achieve here.

12:17.000 --> 12:19.000
We want the plans to be efficient.

12:19.000 --> 12:26.000
We want the process for settling on the plans to be as participatory as possible and democratic.

12:26.000 --> 12:35.000
And in terms of equity, in this case, we're kind of talking about generational equity.

12:35.000 --> 12:43.000
So the first thing we do is make a proposal about how to incentivize the present generation.

12:43.000 --> 12:47.000
We're the only people who can sit down to make a long term plan.

12:47.000 --> 12:51.000
When they're sitting down to make it, it's the present generation that's going to make it.

12:51.000 --> 12:59.000
How can you incentivize them to seriously take into account the interests of future generations?

12:59.000 --> 13:04.000
And we propose that before you do any kind of long term planning at all,

13:04.000 --> 13:14.000
that the present generation has to discuss and vote on what we call a generational equity constraint.

13:14.000 --> 13:19.000
And what the generational equity constraint says is this.

13:19.000 --> 13:31.000
There has to be a limit on how much aggregate consumption can differ from one year to the next.

13:31.000 --> 13:33.000
Here's a dilemma.

13:33.000 --> 13:38.000
Suppose we sit down and we calculate an efficient investment plan.

13:38.000 --> 13:44.000
And because technical change is going to be very, very robust,

13:44.000 --> 13:55.000
it turns out that the efficient investment plan means that consumption in early years is going to be much less the consumption in late years.

13:55.000 --> 14:02.000
There was an example of a country that actually did do a very unfair investment plan.

14:02.000 --> 14:12.000
Stalin's Soviet Union invested such a high percentage during the 1930s and the 1940s

14:12.000 --> 14:17.000
that they literally starved many people in early generations.

14:17.000 --> 14:23.000
Now, you can argue with hindsight that given World War II and Hitler's onslaught,

14:23.000 --> 14:28.000
maybe it's a good thing for human civilization that they did that.

14:28.000 --> 14:34.000
Because it was really the Soviet Union that broke the back of the Nazism.

14:34.000 --> 14:43.000
And had they not been investing 35 percent of GDP during the 1930s,

14:43.000 --> 14:47.000
it's unlikely that they would have managed to resist.

14:47.000 --> 14:52.000
So you can look back and, but clearly there's a problem here.

14:52.000 --> 14:54.000
There's a generational equity problem.

14:54.000 --> 15:01.000
If you invest too much, it may be that when you look at efficiency,

15:01.000 --> 15:09.000
that it would lead you to invest so much that it really is unfair to early generations.

15:09.000 --> 15:13.000
Well, the early generations present, they should be able to take care of that.

15:13.000 --> 15:19.000
And presumably the early generation in the Soviet Union wouldn't have voted to let Stalin do to them what he did.

15:19.000 --> 15:24.000
But in any case, to protect themselves from that, all they have to do is say,

15:24.000 --> 15:32.000
well, we don't accept the long-term plan where consumption this year,

15:32.000 --> 15:38.000
where consumption next year is more than four percent higher than consumption this year.

15:38.000 --> 15:40.000
I'm talking about aggregate consumption.

15:40.000 --> 15:42.000
So they could protect themselves by doing that.

15:42.000 --> 15:46.000
What we have proposed is a way that when they protect themselves,

15:46.000 --> 15:52.000
they will also simultaneously protect future generations who are not present.

15:52.000 --> 15:57.000
That same four percent is going to be used to say, oh,

15:57.000 --> 16:08.000
but it also is unacceptable if present consumption is four percent higher than future consumption.

16:08.000 --> 16:14.000
Why might that happen in an efficient plan when you're making up an efficient plan?

16:14.000 --> 16:23.000
Well, suppose that the environment is deteriorating very rapidly.

16:23.000 --> 16:31.000
That might mean that it's actually hard for future generations to live at the same level that earlier generations are.

16:31.000 --> 16:37.000
Or suppose technological progress is just very low.

16:37.000 --> 16:41.000
So the generational equity constraint, the idea of it is to say,

16:41.000 --> 16:50.000
when we design procedures to come up with the efficient plan, it still might be an unacceptable plan.

16:50.000 --> 16:52.000
It might be unfair to future generations.

16:52.000 --> 16:55.000
It might be unfair to present generation.

16:55.000 --> 17:00.000
And we're going to eliminate that possibility before we even draw the plan up,

17:00.000 --> 17:04.000
before anybody knows what the plan is going to look like.

17:04.000 --> 17:10.000
We're going to basically say consumption in any two adjacent years cannot differ by more than four percent,

17:10.000 --> 17:13.000
no matter in which direction.

17:13.000 --> 17:15.000
So that's our proposal.

17:15.000 --> 17:19.000
And I don't think anybody else has ever suggested something like this.

17:19.000 --> 17:22.000
And as I said, this is unvetted.

17:22.000 --> 17:28.000
But at least it's a serious attempt to take efficient long term,

17:28.000 --> 17:33.000
to recognize one potential problem when you're doing efficient long term planning.

17:33.000 --> 17:44.000
And that is it might inadvertently be unfair to either present generations compared to future generations or vice versa.

17:44.000 --> 17:47.000
So that's that's the first thing.

17:47.000 --> 17:57.000
Then the question reduces to what are the different terms in terms of benefits and the costs that you would take into account when you're doing different kinds of planning?

17:57.000 --> 18:07.000
The only thing you have to take into account when you're doing investment planning for capital goods or investment goods is this consumption in every year.

18:07.000 --> 18:11.000
And these capital goods contribute to consumption.

18:11.000 --> 18:21.000
There are no particular other benefits that come from producing a machine or we can produce shoe making machines or we can produce shoes.

18:21.000 --> 18:28.000
And the only benefits that come from from shoe making machines are just more shoes at a different time period.

18:28.000 --> 18:31.000
That's not true for education.

18:31.000 --> 18:35.000
And that's not true for the environment.

18:35.000 --> 18:44.000
I mean, as a lifetime educator, I don't think the primary purpose of education is producing a more productive workforce.

18:44.000 --> 18:53.000
I think it's the primary purpose of education is enabling people to enjoy life more fully.

18:53.000 --> 19:06.000
And I also think a primary purpose of education is preparing everybody to participate democratically in every kind of decision making, including economic decision making.

19:06.000 --> 19:20.000
So those are benefits from educate from investing in education that go that are above and beyond an additional that really are not benefits that from making more machines.

19:20.000 --> 19:33.000
So the first thing you have to do is you have to sit down and figure out, well, what are all the benefits that come from more education and who would be best suited to estimating what those are likely to be?

19:34.000 --> 19:38.000
And then you have to weigh that against the cost of investing in anything.

19:38.000 --> 19:45.000
And the cost of investing in anything today is there's less consumption today.

19:45.000 --> 19:48.000
So you can write up the efficiency conditions for education.

19:48.000 --> 19:54.000
You can write up the efficiency conditions for what's the efficient amount to invest in machines.

19:54.000 --> 19:57.000
And the same thing holds for the environment.

19:57.000 --> 20:12.000
So in the case of the environment, you know, environmental economists spend a tremendous amount of time trying to estimate what they call the use value of environmental amenities to consumers.

20:12.000 --> 20:23.000
So the environment plays a role in production when you think of the environment as being natural capital.

20:23.000 --> 20:28.000
You need land to grow food on.

20:28.000 --> 20:30.000
You need water.

20:30.000 --> 20:31.000
You need oil.

20:31.000 --> 20:34.000
The environment also is something we enjoy.

20:34.000 --> 20:37.000
We go vacation in it.

20:37.000 --> 20:51.000
So there's use value for national parks and you want, you know, and, and then another thing that environmental economists recognize is that there's something called existence value that people place.

20:51.000 --> 20:59.000
For instance, I will never go to the ANWR National Preserve up in northern Alaska.

20:59.000 --> 21:01.000
I will never go there.

21:01.000 --> 21:13.000
That doesn't mean I do not put value on the fact that it exists and we're not going to open up those oil leases that would destroy that park.

21:13.000 --> 21:24.000
So that's called sort of, so when you're trying to sort of evaluate environment and how much we should protect it, these are things that environmental economists take into account.

21:24.000 --> 21:26.000
They should.

21:26.000 --> 21:43.000
So roughly speaking, there's a consumption value to a protected or enhanced environment, as well as we're preserving it as a capital asset and not drawing it down so fast that we have nothing left later.

21:43.000 --> 22:01.000
So all of these things have to be taken into account and you have to identify, well, who would be the best people to task with estimating what these somewhat unknowable benefits are going to be in the future?

22:01.000 --> 22:11.000
And who are we going to task with estimating the cost of protecting the environment or the cost of producing the education in the future?

22:11.000 --> 22:24.000
And so what we have done is we've sort of carefully gone through and tried to identify what consumer federations or producer federations would be best.

22:24.000 --> 22:44.000
You have to look at two things. Who actually would have better knowledge about what these effects are going to be and who might have a tendency, who might have an incentive to either over or underestimate a particular effect.

22:44.000 --> 22:56.000
So we've tried to do is carefully take those things into account and make tentative proposals about who would you put in charge of making these estimates?

22:56.000 --> 23:12.000
And then the planning agency, you can have an environmental planning agency, an educational planning agency, you can just have some, you can have an investment planning agency sort of take those estimates and calculate what the efficient plan would be in each case.

23:12.000 --> 23:23.000
Now we're not done. First thing we have to do is test that against the generational equity constraint.

23:23.000 --> 23:32.000
Because that plan might violate the generational equity constraint, in which case it's got to be revised and modified.

23:32.000 --> 23:38.000
Now you've done that. It either didn't violate or it's revised and modified.

23:38.000 --> 23:49.000
What do you then have to do? Well, at that point, we think there needs to be a debate.

23:49.000 --> 23:58.000
There needs to be a vote. Is that debate and vote something that's done through the national legislature and the political system?

23:58.000 --> 24:07.000
So what we're talking about is approving a long run environmental plan, approving an education plan, approving an investment plan.

24:07.000 --> 24:18.000
How do you do that at this point? It could be through legislature discussion debate.

24:18.000 --> 24:27.000
It could be put to a referendum. So we're agnostic of all that. I mean, that's what we're saying. Of course, at that point, it should be handled democratic.

24:27.000 --> 24:39.000
The place where we think we've done something clever and discovered something that I don't know if other people have discovered is this.

24:39.000 --> 24:55.000
We know that whatever plan has been drawn up, check with the generational equity constraint, discuss, debated, voted on.

24:55.000 --> 25:06.000
It will it will be mistaken. There will be mistakes because we will have estimated some things wrong.

25:06.000 --> 25:18.000
So it's really important to figure out, is there some way to identify when a mistake has been made and is there something you can do about it before it's too late?

25:18.000 --> 25:29.000
And what we discovered is that when you look at the results we get from annual plans, so suppose we do an investment plan for 10 years, it's all approved.

25:29.000 --> 25:37.000
It's implemented. We also have to have an annual plan for the first year during that investment plan.

25:37.000 --> 25:46.000
Now, that annual plan, the investment plan will already tell us how many machines of different kinds we have to produce during that year.

25:46.000 --> 25:53.000
The investment plan has decided how much investment goods have to be produced during the first year.

25:53.000 --> 26:12.000
So that's a given when we do the annual planning. But at the end of that first year, there is information that will tell us whether or not it actually turned out that we produced the right number of machines.

26:12.000 --> 26:21.000
That the results of the annual plan will tell us that there was something wrong with the 10-year investment plan.

26:21.000 --> 26:31.000
Now, the important thing, I mean, the important thing is there's still nine years that we can correct for. You can't correct for the first year.

26:31.000 --> 26:39.000
It took you a year to discover that something you estimated in the investment plan was actually wrong.

26:40.000 --> 26:47.000
The results of the first year showed you it was wrong. That's the clever thing we figured out.

26:47.000 --> 26:55.000
You can't go back and undo the first year. So you already invested a little bit wrong in that first year.

26:55.000 --> 26:59.000
You can't do anything about that. But you've got nine years left.

26:59.000 --> 27:07.000
And there's no reason you can't revise the investment plan after the first year in light of what you just discovered.

27:07.000 --> 27:12.000
And that mitigates the sort of welfare losses for the next nine years.

27:12.000 --> 27:18.000
And you can do that every year. And of course, it's even more important to do that for your environmental plans.

27:18.000 --> 27:30.000
And more important, the longer the planning period, the more important it is, the longer the planning period, the more mistakes the plan will make.

27:30.000 --> 27:38.000
The longer the planning period, the harder it is to estimate what those future effects are going to be.

27:38.000 --> 27:53.000
Therefore, the longer the planning period, the more valuable it is to be able to identify the errors and then revise that long term plan in order to sort of mitigate the damages.

27:53.000 --> 28:02.000
And that's essentially the logic of what we presented for the first time here in part five of the Democratic Planning Book.

28:02.000 --> 28:12.000
And I would just say it's unvetted. It's not unvetted in the sense that it hasn't been successfully passed by peer review and published in economic journals.

28:12.000 --> 28:19.000
Because the logic is the same whether it's investment planning, education planning or environmental planning.

28:19.000 --> 28:34.000
And so it went through the proposal for the investment planning and this whole procedure for identifying errors and correcting errors that we submitted to an economic journal and it's been accepted.

28:34.000 --> 28:48.000
I don't think it's in print yet, but at least it went through sort of a pretty careful review process from some reviewers who were very skeptical that we had managed to accomplish what we were claiming.

28:48.000 --> 29:10.000
Yeah, I mean, all of the things that you just described within your last answer, what all of this kind of emits as a feeling maybe or what I see coming back into the model of Perricon is allowing more of a political process on a macro level within the model.

29:10.000 --> 29:33.000
And this is something I highly appreciate because when you were talking about the anarchist skepticism towards the IFB, the Iteration Facilitation Board, I kind of share this anarchist skepticism towards central plant economies for sure because I'm not a big fan of central plant economies.

29:33.000 --> 29:49.000
Definitely, but what I, on the other hand, like myths within the IFB are, and maybe this came through through my questions, are like political processes that might like assist the parametric ones.

29:49.000 --> 30:00.000
And within this long term planning, I see this political debate, this need for radical deliberation as a process coming back into the model.

30:00.000 --> 30:17.000
And I highly appreciate it, I have to say, because if I understand you correctly, there might be these people who are tasked with like finding out how to do things in the most efficient and ideal way.

30:17.000 --> 30:32.000
But at the end, they will have to produce some form of plan, ideally plans, a landscape of different plans that will then be decided upon through a political process, as I understand it.

30:32.000 --> 30:49.000
And this is something I think is the actually only way to go, because you cannot go about these questions, education, environment, long term planning, long term investment, just via some form of like utility function, so to speak.

30:50.000 --> 31:00.000
No, I think, you know, this is very interesting. And what's curious is, we almost have opposite reactions.

31:00.000 --> 31:08.000
So you were looking at the annual planning and saying, there's no real planning here.

31:08.000 --> 31:19.000
And there's certainly no sort of political process that's guiding the planning, it seems just nobody is having to think about all of these things.

31:19.000 --> 31:32.000
There's this thinking in terms of my own self activity proposal, and a very quick yes or no approving of others based on a very obvious criteria.

31:33.000 --> 31:41.000
Where is the discussion, the debate, because there are complicated things about economics, where is the discussion, the debate, it's not there.

31:41.000 --> 31:48.000
And then you're looking at our proposals about investment and long term development planning and saying, well, this is more pleasing to me.

31:48.000 --> 32:06.000
It's the kind of thing that I've, and I have the opposite reaction, because, and actually there's various places in part five of the book, where I point out what I believe are some unfortunate consequences.

32:06.000 --> 32:26.000
And the unfortunate consequences are, when you look at who we propose would be involved in the generation of the plan, it's consumer federations, it's industry federations of workers councils.

32:26.000 --> 32:30.000
Those are delegates.

32:31.000 --> 32:39.000
That's already one whole huge level removed from an actual worker, an actual consumer.

32:39.000 --> 32:47.000
So what I like about the annual planning is, it's the actual workers and actual consumers who are doing it.

32:47.000 --> 33:01.000
And what I find, what I find worrisome about the more long term planning stuff is that it's already one level removed from the ordinary citizen.

33:01.000 --> 33:22.000
Now we can make sure that the people involved are represented, they're representing, and the procedures for having them elected to be the representatives are very democratic.

33:22.000 --> 33:33.000
But I worry about it as, for the ordinary person, does it just sort of, I don't know, there was a whole bunch of long term plans that were drawn up.

33:33.000 --> 33:36.000
I don't remember ever being involved in any of that.

33:36.000 --> 33:49.000
So I almost see it as a necessary evil, that the objective conditions basically leave us no other choice.

33:49.000 --> 34:02.000
When we're coming up with sensible procedures that are democratic, I want them to be efficient, I want them to be fair, I want them to be democratic.

34:02.000 --> 34:14.000
I can do all that, but I can't make them as participatory as in your own workers council, you propose what you want to make and how you want to make it and nobody can revise it except for you.

34:14.000 --> 34:17.000
I can't do that. And that upsets me.

34:19.000 --> 34:24.000
That's very interesting. I mean, there you go. I'd say there you go.

34:24.000 --> 34:35.000
There you go. There are questions that cannot be addressed within what is called in Paragon at some point, a self-sovereign workers council, if I'm correct.

34:35.000 --> 34:53.000
And so there is not, I would answer maybe in this direction, whether it is on an individual level as a human being or on the level of the workers council, there's always these interdependencies that you yourself always talk about and point towards.

34:53.000 --> 35:14.000
And this necessarily creates levels of engagement that are beyond this level of autonomy, the fiction of autonomy on this level that you yourself are able to influence in the manner that you would like it to be in the form of direct participation.

35:15.000 --> 35:24.000
There's one other thing that I think is rather curious or interesting about the investment in the long-term development planning.

35:24.000 --> 35:29.000
There's a world in which we have to argue about what kind of economy we like.

35:29.000 --> 35:45.000
And then there's a much bigger world that has been having an argument over whether or not capitalism, actual real world economies, should be more or less planned than they are.

35:45.000 --> 35:50.000
And that's a debate that's gone on since the beginning of capitalism.

35:51.000 --> 36:02.000
And what we have just lived through the past 40 years was a huge swing away from planning toward just let the market rip.

36:04.000 --> 36:10.000
And of course, different countries have always been in different places on that spectrum.

36:10.000 --> 36:17.000
But globally, the spectrum has moved dramatically away from planning.

36:17.000 --> 36:35.000
I think that that has proven to be such a palpable sort of mistake that we will see revived interest in planning amongst people who don't give a shit about socialism.

36:36.000 --> 36:55.000
And I actually think some of the things that we have now recommended about how a desirable economy would tackle these issues are likely to become of interest to others who are not interested in a truly desirable economy or socialism of any kind.

36:55.000 --> 37:12.000
You know, before our debates about market socialism versus Cockshop and Cottrell's Scottish model of planning or the Albert Hanell participatory economy annual planning, because I do think that there are two contributions.

37:12.000 --> 37:18.000
So intellectual contributions to this sort of part five of the book.

37:18.000 --> 37:25.000
And one is that the rest of the world is not going to be interested in the generational equity constraint.

37:25.000 --> 37:33.000
But the rest of the world is going to be very interested in how the results of what just happened this year.

37:33.000 --> 37:40.000
They identify where you made mistakes in your long term plan, and there's plenty of time to make corrections.

37:40.000 --> 37:53.000
So that contribution is something that anybody doing long term planning of any kind, no matter what kind of economy they're interested in, should actually be very interested in.

37:53.000 --> 38:07.000
The other thing is, I sense amongst the younger generation, there's a real sense amongst the younger generation that they want economic decision making to be more democratic and participatory.

38:07.000 --> 38:17.000
Their nightmare is going to work for a global capitalist corporation or only the where they're just clogs in the wheel until they join management.

38:17.000 --> 38:38.000
So I think that since what we have proposed is how can you do long run planning and make it as participatory as possible and make it democratic also in the end, that that will be an attractive idea to progressive politically minded people.

38:38.000 --> 38:45.000
And it's in some sense separable from all the rest of the sort of model of a participatory economy.

38:45.000 --> 38:58.000
So I think that there's sort of an opportunity for us to make some headway in some to make some headway in some political circles that are much broader than our usual ones.

38:58.000 --> 39:10.000
And all progress will only come, you know, when you have maximized your allies, even if they're temporary.

39:10.000 --> 39:21.000
So I think that's also another area in which when we do have sort of a fully vetting of all this about the proposals about doing long term.

39:21.000 --> 39:39.000
The other thing is, there's nothing in these proposals about doing long term strategic, you know, strategic international long term planning, education planning, environmental planning, investment planning, that if I were David Schweikert and I had proposed the model of

39:39.000 --> 39:42.000
market socialism.

39:42.000 --> 39:47.000
That still isn't an answer about how do you go about doing planning.

39:47.000 --> 39:57.000
I mean, that's, that's an alternative answer to don't do the annual planning, the participatory annual planning, don't do the central planning and a comprehensive central planning.

39:57.000 --> 40:05.000
Leave all that to the markets and make sure that there's no capitalist owners of the workplaces have those be workers councils.

40:05.000 --> 40:11.000
But the essence of his proposal simply at that point is and let markets decide all that.

40:11.000 --> 40:28.000
And he really doesn't have any sensible proposal, the market socialists don't have sensible proposals about, they don't really they really don't make proposals, just like we, you know, for all these years didn't really make any concrete proposals about procedures for coming up with

40:28.000 --> 40:41.000
investment and development plans and checking them for inevitable errors and then who gets to vote on them finally and how is it debated and decided in the end.

40:41.000 --> 40:55.000
All of our competitors in the debate about alternatives to capitalism have really said very little about that and there's no reason that any one of them couldn't go ahead and use this as their answer to that question.

40:55.000 --> 40:59.000
So there will be new alliances.

40:59.000 --> 41:03.000
Don't expect David Schweiker to agree with that, by the way.

41:03.000 --> 41:22.000
No, but I mean, I like the idea that you that you say okay, we have this building block now that addresses a whole bunch of questions concerning the question of planning as such, that might be attractive for a whole bunch of different people that that we were that are not our core

41:22.000 --> 41:32.000
clientele, so to speak. And so this might be something that that further fuels this renaissance of planning, so to speak.

41:32.000 --> 41:34.000
So this is a quite a nice idea.

41:34.000 --> 41:57.000
I think that's the payoff for us. The payoff for us is if for 40 years neoliberalism gave planning a bad economic planning a bad reputation demeaned and convinced a large body of the global populace that you know it was just an inefficient mistake.

41:57.000 --> 42:06.000
Well, the fact that Chinese capitalism is out competing US capitalism hands over fist is because they have a more planned version of capitalism.

42:06.000 --> 42:15.000
So I think there's all sorts of reasons and there's no way you can solve climate change without a lot more planning.

42:15.000 --> 42:29.000
So, I look forward to I can see reasonable reasons to expect that the reputation of planning is going to be rescued from the rubbing it took during the 40 year neoliberal period.

42:29.000 --> 42:38.000
And that in and of itself is going to make it easier for us to talk about all of the stuff we want to talk about.

42:38.000 --> 42:58.000
So I think that's a plus for us. Not only do we have some ideas they could make use of. I think that anything that makes people more have a more friendly attitude toward the idea of economic planning is just got to help us going forward.

42:58.000 --> 43:13.000
I'm very much interested in the question of real life paragon examples and specifically whether or not there are examples of experiments that you know of that really try to tackle the question of scale.

43:13.000 --> 43:23.000
So maybe even that try to make use of modern information and communication technologies in order to tackle this question of scale.

43:23.000 --> 43:37.000
Do you know of any such experiments that try to envision an idea, not only envision an idea of paragon, but to also practice it?

43:37.000 --> 43:47.000
Good question. And at some point we're going to connect this up to the issue of transition strategy.

43:47.000 --> 44:05.000
So let me sow a seed for that connection that will come. Very broadly speaking, I think transition strategy comes down to two rather different kinds of things.

44:05.000 --> 44:25.000
Two rather different kinds of organizing activities. One of which I call building and strengthening progressive social movements, the labor movement, the women's movement, the anti-racist movement, the anti-corporate movement.

44:25.000 --> 44:39.000
These are all progressive movements where there are clearly problems in capitalism, in the existing society that clearly need to be addressed.

44:39.000 --> 44:46.000
Large numbers of people are adversely affected by the problems that these different movements address.

44:46.000 --> 45:04.000
So this is the opportunity for us to reach out to the broadest number of people and engage with them in activities that can win substantial victories even without economic system change.

45:04.000 --> 45:24.000
And then the question becomes how do you participate in those movements in ways that not only win reforms, but also lead people to want even greater reforms and come to the conclusion that that can't happen at some point unless you have fundamental system change.

45:24.000 --> 45:47.000
The other activity, the other major kind of organizing activity that I think is going to be necessary in many places for a successful transition is what I call building and creating real life experiences and equitable cooperation.

45:47.000 --> 46:02.000
And that's actually organizing activities where we're starting to put into place what we are saying we want the entire economy and society to be able to do.

46:02.000 --> 46:12.000
Now historically, probably the oldest example is this, is workers-owned cooperatives.

46:12.000 --> 46:26.000
And there's a tendency amongst leftists to basically see our entire history as being the labor movement and unions.

46:26.000 --> 46:39.000
And yet you could argue, particularly right now, the labor movement and unions in the United States are probably weaker than they have been.

46:39.000 --> 46:48.000
You'd have to go back to the 1870s to find a period where the labor movement in the United States is as weak as it is presently.

46:49.000 --> 47:03.000
So it's rather interesting that, on the other hand, the movement for workers cooperatives in the United States is not in such heavy decline as the labor movement is.

47:03.000 --> 47:17.000
So that's one area. And I would say that workers cooperatives, now you want an example of workers cooperatives that's, and in terms of scale, some of them are rather large.

47:18.000 --> 47:20.000
I mean, take a look at northern Italy.

47:22.000 --> 47:35.000
I think a third of the economic activity in northern Italy is activity that is this whole system of sort of workers cooperatives and cooperatives that operates in northern Italy.

47:35.000 --> 47:40.000
Or you look at Mondragon, you know, in the Basque region of Spain.

47:40.000 --> 47:44.000
So some of these are not little tiny experiments.

47:44.000 --> 47:50.000
Another example I would give is the whole idea of participatory budgeting.

47:51.000 --> 47:54.000
And it's very interesting.

47:54.000 --> 48:04.000
This idea came up in two places in the world, and I know from personal experience that neither one of them was aware of what was going on in the other place.

48:05.000 --> 48:14.000
So this idea that we want to do participatory budgeting, what does that mean?

48:14.000 --> 48:23.000
Well, city budgets are basically decided by sort of the city government bureaucracy.

48:24.000 --> 48:41.000
And in Porto Alegre, Brazil, the Workers' Party, the Lula Workers' Party, came up with the idea that, you know, we want some percentage of the tax revenues of the city to be set aside.

48:41.000 --> 48:55.000
And how they are used should be decided by different neighborhoods in the city are going to have assemblies, and they're going to go through a process of discussing how it is they'd like to have that money spent.

48:55.000 --> 49:02.000
They're part of the money. They're going to decide how it's spent through some sort of neighborhood assemblies.

49:05.000 --> 49:08.000
And that was what they called a participatory budgeting.

49:08.000 --> 49:30.000
And at the same time, one of the most leftist states in India, which is Kerala, India, that the, in Kerala, India, there was a period, I mean, actually the Communist Party has been the ruling party in Kerala, India, two or three different times over the past 50 years.

49:31.000 --> 49:40.000
And they had a more or less traditional sort of Marxist and Communist program when they governed.

49:40.000 --> 49:58.000
And then in the early 2000s, a new generation of leaders in that party in Kerala, India, said, you know, when we govern, we basically have been trying to implement serve the people programs.

50:00.000 --> 50:03.000
But that's not really what we're all about.

50:04.000 --> 50:10.000
We also want to empower people to make decisions about how they best serve themselves.

50:11.000 --> 50:21.000
And so they also pioneered a participatory budgeting process, and they ran on that platform and they were elected on that platform.

50:21.000 --> 50:39.000
And for about a period of 10 years before they were voted out of power, they implemented this very elaborate participatory budgeting process where they literally had 20% of the population attending assemblies and meetings.

50:39.000 --> 50:46.000
Making decisions about how they wanted to see the tax revenues spent on what kinds of projects and what kinds of programs.

50:46.000 --> 50:54.000
Well, obviously, participatory budgeting, you know, is, it's two things.

50:54.000 --> 50:58.000
It's an expression to the fact that this is something people want.

50:58.000 --> 51:11.000
It's an expression of the fact that it also affords us real life experience about what are the pros and cons of trying to organize it in one kind of way or another kind of way.

51:11.000 --> 51:17.000
Participatory economic decision making about how it is we want things done.

51:17.000 --> 51:26.000
And it also, to the degree that it is successful, and in both these places, it was remarkably successful.

51:26.000 --> 51:37.000
I mean, it wasn't lack of success in these programs that led to the electoral defeat of the Workers' Party in Brazil or the Communist Party in Kerala.

51:37.000 --> 51:44.000
These programs were popular. Their electoral defeat was due to other causes.

51:44.000 --> 52:03.000
It also just, it builds people's confidence that these kinds of things work and that they aren't just pie in the sky and somehow all these important economic decisions are best left to somebody else.

52:03.000 --> 52:07.000
So those are some examples of big things.

52:07.000 --> 52:27.000
Now, I mentioned that there were a couple of places, very small types of operations that really tried to implement the entire proposal, including effort and sacrifice rating and balancing jobs for empowerment and all of that.

52:27.000 --> 52:35.000
And there were a series of small collectives that were organized jointly. It was called the A-Zone.

52:35.000 --> 52:42.000
And they had a series of buildings in the city of Winnipeg in Canada.

52:42.000 --> 52:55.000
And, I mean, the businesses, there was a bicycle repair business, there was a recording studio record business, there was a restaurant, there was the Mondragon Cafe restaurant.

52:55.000 --> 53:04.000
They did a bicycle delivery program. I couldn't believe they delivered bicycles through the winter in Winnipeg when the snow was six feet high.

53:04.000 --> 53:11.000
Obviously, this is a seasonal business. No? What do you mean seasonal? We deliver all year round.

53:11.000 --> 53:19.000
In any case, so these people had read about participatory economics and said, we're going to do it.

53:19.000 --> 53:30.000
We're going to at least do the part that has to do with how would a workers council run, you know, in these ways. And they did it for about 15 to 20 years.

53:30.000 --> 53:39.000
And there's a really rich experience there of what sort of problems did they run into, what kinds of conflicts came up, what worked, what didn't work.

53:39.000 --> 53:46.000
And I can tell you that one of the things that was most problematic was the effort rating.

53:46.000 --> 53:52.000
And whether or not people were comfortable with it, whether they weren't comfortable with it, how to go about it, what to do about it.

53:52.000 --> 53:55.000
And that's a rich experience to learn from.

53:55.000 --> 54:15.000
The other place that very self-consciously applied, you know, tried to apply all these was the South End Press, which was a left press in Boston for they did finally go out of business about four or five years ago now.

54:15.000 --> 54:25.000
But it was a very successful left press, you know, in the United States that operated for about 30 years.

54:25.000 --> 54:36.000
And it was always organized along the, according to the principles of participatory economy in terms of balancing jobs, remuneration, all of that.

54:36.000 --> 54:44.000
And if you take a look at other left presses, they're basically a pretty standard business model.

54:44.000 --> 54:59.000
Usually there is some sort of major donor who has sort of poured a lot of money into it, but then it runs more or less, you know, the same way that other publishers, you know, book publishers do.

54:59.000 --> 55:14.000
And there was a big question about, well, is South End Press going to be, is the standard business model for a publisher going to prove to be more competitively successful in the book publishing industry than South End Press is?

55:14.000 --> 55:20.000
Which is insisting on apply, you know, running itself in a very, very different way.

55:20.000 --> 55:28.000
And you could say, well, South End Press no longer exists, but it wasn't because it wasn't successful at publishing book for all those years.

55:28.000 --> 55:46.000
It was amongst the most successful of left publishing houses in the United States during the time of its operation, which provides some evidence that, no, these things aren't so in, these ideas and suggestions about how better to organize work processes.

55:46.000 --> 56:05.000
They aren't so limiting to productivity that people applying those principles and working in that way cannot be perfectly successful in competition with businesses that are being run along standard or what you might call capitalist principles.

56:05.000 --> 56:10.000
I have some macro and some micro questions, I guess.

56:10.000 --> 56:33.000
Let's start with the micro ones, because you stated that taken from the real life experience, one of the most problematic aspects of Perikan that was causing the most trouble was the, this idea of effort ratings that one judges his or her coworker,

56:33.000 --> 56:37.000
and then the remuneration would be coupled to this kind of judgment.

56:37.000 --> 56:51.000
And when I was reading about Perikan, this was immediately something that I could not get along with because I immediately thought this will definitely lead to some sort of toxic environment.

56:51.000 --> 57:03.000
So if you hear about these experiments and then people who actually try to implement these ideas and they give you the feedback that this is something that actually did not work out,

57:03.000 --> 57:09.000
why do you then stick to this principle in your most recent work, for example?

57:09.000 --> 57:27.000
Why don't you, because usually one would think that this would lead you to a point where you would have to revise the idea of effort ratings and maybe stick to a different kind of model of how remuneration could be addressed, as you did with housework and care work.

57:27.000 --> 57:35.000
Okay, first of all, so let me just say sort of three things to situate the discussion.

57:35.000 --> 57:41.000
Our actual proposal is that workers councils do whatever the hell they want in this regard.

57:41.000 --> 57:49.000
So, I have no trouble taking that position, but I consider that to be a principal position.

57:49.000 --> 58:00.000
And the second thing is, while we recommend that you would want to do something about this, we leave it up to you how to do it.

58:00.000 --> 58:23.000
And I am sure that if there were a participatory economy with hundreds of thousands of different workplaces, that there would be a huge difference in how different workplaces went on, you know, decided to go about this, including when they decided to do anything along these lines at all.

58:23.000 --> 58:28.000
And I don't think that's a bad thing.

58:28.000 --> 58:35.000
Because here's an area where we're not sure how work, we're not really sure how things work out.

58:35.000 --> 58:53.000
And in that context, whenever you find yourself in that situation, having a social experiment where you have a very wide variety of people trying things that are quite different from one another is sort of a sensible way to find out what works best and what doesn't.

58:53.000 --> 59:05.000
The third thing I'd say is, I think there's a huge difference between leftists and normal people on this subject.

59:05.000 --> 59:14.000
Most leftist reaction to, do I want somebody sitting in judgment about whether I'm working very hard?

59:14.000 --> 59:20.000
Do I want to sit in judgment of my co-workers about whether they're working very hard?

59:20.000 --> 59:26.000
Most leftists just don't like that.

59:26.000 --> 59:29.000
I don't like it.

59:29.000 --> 59:36.000
I would choose a workplace where we all were more or less on the honor system.

59:37.000 --> 59:40.000
I mean, where would I want to work in a participatory economy?

59:40.000 --> 59:48.000
I would look for a place that was on the honor system extreme of the spectrum, because that's what I would be most comfortable with.

59:48.000 --> 01:00:02.000
Both from the point of view of whether somebody else is judging whether I've been working very hard and whether I want to really get myself in the, do I want to put myself in a position where I'm getting into fellow workers' faces about, you haven't been working very hard this last month.

01:00:02.000 --> 01:00:15.000
But I don't think that, I think there's a huge difference between people who are already progressive and leftist on this subject in terms of their own personal attitudes and normal people.

01:00:15.000 --> 01:00:30.000
I think amongst normal people, the whole idea that, well, if the people that I'm working with aren't working very hard, and I am, I got a problem with that.

01:00:30.000 --> 01:00:45.000
And are you proposing an economic system where I would just become victim of a bunch of, you know, a bunch of gold-brickers and slaggers in my own workplace, and they're going to, you're telling me that they're going to get paid the same thing I am?

01:00:45.000 --> 01:00:48.000
There's no remedy for that.

01:00:48.000 --> 01:00:51.000
So that's where I come down on it.

01:00:51.000 --> 01:00:54.000
I'm not surprised it's controversial.

01:00:54.000 --> 01:01:01.000
I think the average sentiment amongst leftists and people who aren't leftists is actually rather remarkably different on the subject.

01:01:01.000 --> 01:01:13.000
I also think that what we leftists want and are comfortable with might require a learning process.

01:01:13.000 --> 01:01:31.000
It's not that what we want isn't better, but it might be that we need a history of people being responsible to their workmates.

01:01:31.000 --> 01:01:33.000
We need a history of that.

01:01:33.000 --> 01:01:43.000
I think the thing that's annoying or troubling is making invidious comparisons.

01:01:43.000 --> 01:01:50.000
We don't want people making invidious comparisons about us, and we don't want to make invidious comparisons about other people.

01:01:50.000 --> 01:02:00.000
Well, the way to avoid the necessity of invidious comparisons is a historical track record of people behaving responsibly.

01:02:00.000 --> 01:02:13.000
Once people discover that people are behaving more and more responsibly because things are set up so that you're rewarded for behaving responsibly,

01:02:13.000 --> 01:02:26.000
once people discover that that's the case, then I think that my expectation would be that the amount of time and energy that goes into effort rating

01:02:26.000 --> 01:02:34.000
or sort of trying to measure whether somebody made a greater or lesser sacrifice than somebody else for purposes of compensation,

01:02:34.000 --> 01:02:39.000
the amount of time and energy and people just paying attention to that.

01:02:39.000 --> 01:02:45.000
There's a reason that economic justice is such an incredibly important touch point for everybody,

01:02:45.000 --> 01:02:53.000
because we have all been victims of economic injustice and we've witnessed and experienced economic injustice.

01:02:53.000 --> 01:02:58.000
So it's a hot issue.

01:02:58.000 --> 01:03:02.000
People care a hell of a lot about it, and they should, and we should.

01:03:02.000 --> 01:03:13.000
But will that be the case in a society where economic injustice has basically, I mean, you're never going to completely eliminate it.

01:03:13.000 --> 01:03:19.000
But where economic injustice is no longer sort of a prime concern in people's lives,

01:03:19.000 --> 01:03:29.000
well, then is it unreasonable to expect that people will just care less about it and therefore put less time and energy into whatever sort of systems

01:03:29.000 --> 01:03:37.000
people would set up to go about measuring, you know, whether there's differences in sacrifices.

01:03:37.000 --> 01:03:45.000
The other thing is the one other thing I'll say on this subject is I don't think there's any dishonor in putting in less effort.

01:03:45.000 --> 01:03:57.000
I don't want to work at maximum effort intensity all the time.

01:03:57.000 --> 01:04:02.000
Now, my wife is a very different personality.

01:04:02.000 --> 01:04:05.000
She almost can't stop herself from doing it.

01:04:05.000 --> 01:04:13.000
But I do recognize that on average she's putting in more effort when she goes to work than what I do.

01:04:13.000 --> 01:04:22.000
And I'm perfectly happy to accept that my compensation would be somewhat less.

01:04:22.000 --> 01:04:39.000
So the proposal is, I think we want to leave people with the personal choice of just how intensely, you know, how much sacrifice and how much effort do you want to sink into your work activity

01:04:39.000 --> 01:04:42.000
as compared to working in working less hours.

01:04:42.000 --> 01:04:47.000
That's easy or working in a more laid back way.

01:04:47.000 --> 01:04:51.000
I think that's something that I'm happy to leave up the personal choice.

01:04:51.000 --> 01:05:04.000
On the other hand, as somebody who would choose a more leisurely sort of pace of work, then I'm happy to accept somewhat less compensation for the fact for that.

01:05:04.000 --> 01:05:07.000
That's my personal choice.

01:05:07.000 --> 01:05:13.000
And I'm happy to accept somewhat less compensation and somebody who's going to work more intensively.

01:05:13.000 --> 01:05:18.000
I'm perfectly happy and think they deserve to have somewhat more compensation.

01:05:18.000 --> 01:05:21.000
Anyway, those are my thoughts on the subject.

01:05:22.000 --> 01:05:32.000
And it's been amongst people's reactions to the sort of participatory economics proposal.

01:05:32.000 --> 01:05:36.000
It's been one of the things where the reaction has been sort of most strong.

01:05:36.000 --> 01:05:38.000
There's absolutely no doubt about that.

01:05:38.000 --> 01:05:48.000
In the history of socialism, the subject that there's been an equal amount of controversy on is a little bit different, though.

01:05:48.000 --> 01:06:06.000
In the history of socialism, basically, the debate has been does everybody get paid the same per hour of work would be one or if your work is more socially valuable than my work, do you deserve to get paid more?

01:06:06.000 --> 01:06:11.000
That's been debated hot and heavily throughout the history of socialism.

01:06:11.000 --> 01:06:25.000
And the spectrum on that has varied back and forth in every country that called itself socialist, you know, during the entire 20th century.

01:06:25.000 --> 01:06:28.000
This is a little different. It's a different controversy.

01:06:28.000 --> 01:06:33.000
It's a different place. It's a different issue that many people have a difference of opinion on.

01:06:33.000 --> 01:06:39.000
And I have to say, when I read your book, I absolutely agree with your argument against both of these.

01:06:39.000 --> 01:06:47.000
Against the measurement by labor time and against the measurement by quote unquote contribution.

01:06:47.000 --> 01:06:59.000
But I have to add I'm also against remuneration according to effort and sacrifice because what you just did, you kind of picked a more or less uncontroversial situation

01:06:59.000 --> 01:07:08.000
where you yourself agree with the assessment that you did not put as much effort into the work than somebody else than your wife.

01:07:08.000 --> 01:07:21.000
But of course, the difficult thing to do would be to decide within situations where the person that thinks she or he is putting in a lot of effort,

01:07:21.000 --> 01:07:30.000
the self experience of how much effort I put in is not identical to the judgment by one's peers.

01:07:30.000 --> 01:07:35.000
And these are the toxic situations that would make it explosive.

01:07:35.000 --> 01:07:43.000
That's right. If your peers judge you more harshly than your own self judgment is where the conflict comes.

01:07:43.000 --> 01:07:47.000
And let me add on that. I think that will happen.

01:07:47.000 --> 01:07:54.000
And sometimes when I write about it, it happened to me at my university where I worked for 37 years.

01:07:54.000 --> 01:07:59.000
I was undervalued all the time and I got paid less than I should have been.

01:07:59.000 --> 01:08:05.000
And I resented it. And it's very important that will happen.

01:08:05.000 --> 01:08:11.000
I mean, one remedy for that is that you fight. I mean, you have to basically challenge the judgment.

01:08:11.000 --> 01:08:14.000
And then the question is, well, what's the process?

01:08:14.000 --> 01:08:19.000
But the ultimate remedy for that is don't stay where I mean, the only reason I stayed working.

01:08:19.000 --> 01:08:26.000
I eventually left as soon as I could. I mean, I was there for 35 years, but that's because I have four children and I was raised.

01:08:26.000 --> 01:08:30.000
I mean, and my wife had a job and it made no sense to leave.

01:08:30.000 --> 01:08:38.000
And once you're a tenured professor, as much as they underpay you, it's still a great job compared to almost any other job.

01:08:38.000 --> 01:08:46.000
But the remedy, I mean, the remedy for that is make it easy for people to leave.

01:08:46.000 --> 01:08:54.000
If you're not being appreciated where you work, it's not so terrible if it's easy for you to go and find a place.

01:08:54.000 --> 01:09:03.000
And if you're right, if it's easy for you to go find another place to work and if you're right, you'll find one that actually appreciates you more.

01:09:04.000 --> 01:09:09.000
Which proved to be the case in my case when I finally was able to move to a different city.

01:09:09.000 --> 01:09:18.000
I got I got treated much more fairly at the university out here in Portland than I was treated at American University for 34 years.

01:09:18.000 --> 01:09:25.000
It's frustrating when you can't move, but if you can move and if you're right, then that's the remedy.

01:09:25.000 --> 01:09:30.000
Basically, what you're saying is your fellow workers are discriminating against you and it's very bad.

01:09:30.000 --> 01:09:34.000
I mean, it's a very bad feeling. I remember it.

01:09:34.000 --> 01:09:40.000
And I'm not the kind of leftist that pretends these things won't happen even in a good society.

01:09:40.000 --> 01:09:50.000
So the question reduces to when these unfortunate life experiences do happen, then have we got some sort of remedy or way of handling them?

01:09:51.000 --> 01:10:04.000
That's the best that we could do, which means that ease of moving from one worker council to another worker council becomes a very important thing to achieve.

01:10:04.000 --> 01:10:11.000
You want to make it very easy for people to move from one another worker council because there will be all sorts of reasons that people want to move.

01:10:11.000 --> 01:10:18.000
And one of them will be I don't think I'm being treated fairly by my workmates.

01:10:18.000 --> 01:10:25.000
It might not just be remuneration. I mean, there are all sorts of other ways in which your workmates might not be treating you fairly.

01:10:25.000 --> 01:10:33.000
And it's always miserable to stay in contact with a whole bunch of people who aren't treating you fairly.

01:10:33.000 --> 01:10:37.000
Yes. Well, I understand the remark to moving.

01:10:37.000 --> 01:10:45.000
And I think it would take up too much time to go even deeper into the question of whether or not this is a good idea to implement.

01:10:45.000 --> 01:10:54.000
And I very much appreciate the fact that Paracon is so flexible to allow different workers councils to handle this.

01:10:54.000 --> 01:10:58.000
On this issue, it would be disingenuous to say we're flexible on a subject.

01:10:58.000 --> 01:11:05.000
I mean, we've been famously denounced for not being flexible about markets.

01:11:05.000 --> 01:11:12.000
And just because I thought sometimes it helps to draw the battle lines for the discussion,

01:11:12.000 --> 01:11:17.000
I decided to go ahead and call myself a market abolitionist.

01:11:17.000 --> 01:11:23.000
So there are some things that we're not flexible about, but yet this we are flexible about.

01:11:23.000 --> 01:11:31.000
And actually, to be very honest with you, I think some of us who say we are advocates for a participatory economy,

01:11:31.000 --> 01:11:37.000
some of us are more flexible about it and some of us are a little less flexible about it.

01:11:37.000 --> 01:11:42.000
Well, I'm happy to hear that in general about this issue, you're flexible.

01:11:42.000 --> 01:11:49.000
And I'm also happy just as a side note that you are not flexible on the question of markets.

01:11:49.000 --> 01:11:52.000
So I do agree on that part as well.

01:11:52.000 --> 01:11:58.000
Well, so I already stated the micro question, so to speak.

01:11:58.000 --> 01:12:01.000
I have a macro question as well.

01:12:01.000 --> 01:12:09.000
And this would be you just sketched on the one part, examples in terms of workers cooperatives.

01:12:09.000 --> 01:12:16.000
It's very easy to imagine how this might work and how these might lead into situations of, let's say,

01:12:16.000 --> 01:12:26.000
prefigurative politics that might be a place to learn all of the also social skills that you need

01:12:26.000 --> 01:12:33.000
in order to live and work and everything else in a participatory economy.

01:12:33.000 --> 01:12:37.000
So these experiments on a smaller scale are very easy to imagine.

01:12:37.000 --> 01:12:46.000
You also sketched experiments in Kerala and in Porto Alegre in terms of participatory budgeting.

01:12:46.000 --> 01:12:50.000
So now let's go even a step further.

01:12:50.000 --> 01:13:01.000
How would we go about if we wanted to do experiments that are scalable, that are large in scale,

01:13:01.000 --> 01:13:07.000
but are not restricted to, quote unquote, only the question of participatory budgeting,

01:13:07.000 --> 01:13:14.000
but try to implement Perikon in its whole, in a larger context?

01:13:14.000 --> 01:13:21.000
Are there any ideas of how experiments that would try to do this could go about?

01:13:21.000 --> 01:13:28.000
There's two things that you might sort of think about in this regard.

01:13:28.000 --> 01:13:36.000
The easiest one is some leftist movement comes to power in some country,

01:13:36.000 --> 01:13:43.000
and they have no intentions of trying to run a centrally planned economy.

01:13:43.000 --> 01:13:46.000
And they're not disciples of market socialism.

01:13:46.000 --> 01:13:50.000
They're not enamored of markets.

01:13:50.000 --> 01:13:58.000
Could a country go about setting up an economy run in some ways along the lines of a participatory economy?

01:13:58.000 --> 01:14:01.000
Could they do annual participatory planning?

01:14:01.000 --> 01:14:08.000
Could they do the kind of environmental planning and education planning and investment planning that we've outlined?

01:14:08.000 --> 01:14:10.000
Could they try to do that?

01:14:10.000 --> 01:14:16.000
There's no reason that a country, there's no reason that a movement coming to power in any country couldn't try this.

01:14:16.000 --> 01:14:21.000
And situations have arisen where that was a possibility.

01:14:21.000 --> 01:14:30.000
In Sri Lanka, there's what's primarily an ethnic conflict.

01:14:30.000 --> 01:14:41.000
And about a third of the population has been in conflict with the majority population in government for decades and decades and decades.

01:14:41.000 --> 01:14:49.000
And at some point in the early 1990s, it looked like that liberation movement had managed to liberate a third of the island.

01:14:49.000 --> 01:14:56.000
And they were interested in, well, we now have to figure out how to run our economy.

01:14:56.000 --> 01:15:08.000
And I talked with various, I mean, it just so happened that there were students at my university that were connected to that movement.

01:15:08.000 --> 01:15:13.000
It could have happened. It didn't. But it could have happened.

01:15:13.000 --> 01:15:25.000
And it would have provided a real life experiment of some people who were leftists trying to organize the economy in a very different way than any leftists have ever done in history.

01:15:25.000 --> 01:15:30.000
And it would have given us some sort of evidence about what works and what doesn't work.

01:15:30.000 --> 01:15:38.000
I was invited down to Cuba in 1990 to consult with them about their planning system.

01:15:38.000 --> 01:15:48.000
Because there was dissatisfaction amongst Cuban economists and various people in the Cuban planning ministry and the Cuban Communist Party.

01:15:48.000 --> 01:15:52.000
They weren't that happy about how their economy was run.

01:15:52.000 --> 01:15:57.000
And they were interested in ideas about how they might make it.

01:15:57.000 --> 01:16:07.000
Their basic complaint was, our economy is sort of just this slow, sluggish thing that doesn't motivate anybody to do anything.

01:16:07.000 --> 01:16:13.000
And my response was, why are you surprised?

01:16:14.000 --> 01:16:24.000
But you could change your planning system, you know, in a way that actually gave people a reason to care, to participate.

01:16:24.000 --> 01:16:35.000
And one of the things that I've known for a long, long time in the case of Cuba is, very early in the revolution, they established these things called Committees for Defense of the Revolution.

01:16:35.000 --> 01:16:39.000
These are neighborhood committees.

01:16:39.000 --> 01:16:46.000
And I, in some ways, these neighborhood committees have basically, they've done some bad things.

01:16:46.000 --> 01:16:55.000
They've basically become the eyes of the government on, you know, who's a little bit, who's a dissident.

01:16:55.000 --> 01:17:05.000
On the other hand, these neighborhood committees also have a lot of power over, you know, distribution of goods and services.

01:17:05.000 --> 01:17:13.000
And, you know, how it is that new housing is sort of built and who gets, you know, who it's assigned to and things like this.

01:17:13.000 --> 01:17:23.000
So I realized that if you think about a participatory economy, well, there's always workplaces.

01:17:23.000 --> 01:17:35.000
The thing that doesn't exist anywhere that we are saying is an important part of how we think the economy has to be run is our neighborhood consumption councils.

01:17:35.000 --> 01:17:46.000
And what I realized was they actually have the neighborhood consumption councils in Cuba, and we can make them do good things and stop them from doing bad things.

01:17:46.000 --> 01:17:50.000
But they've existed, they've been there for 40 years.

01:17:50.000 --> 01:17:59.000
So, unfortunately, I mean, I consulted there, and this was in 1990, and it was right when the Soviet Union was collapsing.

01:17:59.000 --> 01:18:08.000
And Cuba was entering through no fault of their own into what was called the special period where their GDP basically shrunk by half through no fault of their own.

01:18:08.000 --> 01:18:17.000
And so I was supposed to go down there and consult with economists and various people in the planning ministry about some new, new innovative ideas.

01:18:17.000 --> 01:18:21.000
And nobody had any time for anything other than how the hell are we going to survive this?

01:18:21.000 --> 01:18:25.000
And they barely did. But that's a possibility.

01:18:25.000 --> 01:18:39.000
When Chavez came to power in Venezuela, he invited a lot of people in from around the country to help him try and think through, well, how do we want to do our, I mean, what's our economic policy and program and what's our future economic vision like?

01:18:39.000 --> 01:19:01.000
Because, I mean, I know from a fact from people who were sitting in the meetings that Chavez, who was very, very good close personal friends with Fidel Castro, and Chavez said to Castro, we don't really want to copy your economic model.

01:19:01.000 --> 01:19:07.000
And I also know Fidel Castro said back to him, good, don't.

01:19:07.000 --> 01:19:25.000
And so they were looking for something else. And I consulted twice for an institute that the Chavez government set up explicitly to bring in sort of people from outside the country to help them with various ideas about what was their economic policy, etc.

01:19:25.000 --> 01:19:40.000
And one of the things they did, they created more workers co-ops faster in Venezuela than have ever been created any place as part of their transition to.

01:19:40.000 --> 01:19:49.000
They made good use of the high oil price and basically financed a huge number of workers co-ops.

01:19:49.000 --> 01:19:54.000
Now they were criticized because the failure rate was very high.

01:19:54.000 --> 01:20:05.000
But I thought they were very sensible. They said, look, the failure rate is very high. On the other hand, the ones that didn't fail, there's a lot of them.

01:20:05.000 --> 01:20:22.000
And we had the damn money. So yeah, if you're going to do something big, then there's going to be a higher failure rate because you're going to finance a bunch that really weren't that they were bad bets to survive.

01:20:22.000 --> 01:20:36.000
So they did. They created a rather large, I mean, they created a cooperative sector of their economy, you know, and grew it faster than I think the cooperative sector of any economy has ever grown.

01:20:36.000 --> 01:20:43.000
And they saw it simply as this is part of our, this is part of a transition society, you know.

01:20:43.000 --> 01:20:50.000
And part of their strategy also was they did not want to nationalize.

01:20:50.000 --> 01:21:02.000
Partly for political reasons, they thought that they would, that they would provoke the opposition and they hesitated to nationalize in order not to provoke.

01:21:02.000 --> 01:21:09.000
And partly they didn't nationalize because they said, we don't want to nationalize anything until we know how we're going to run it.

01:21:09.000 --> 01:21:18.000
And we're still trying to figure out how to run it. And that's part of the reason they had brought people like me and a bunch of other people from around the world with

01:21:18.000 --> 01:21:23.000
bright ideas that we were all trying to sell about how you should try and organize your economy.

01:21:23.000 --> 01:21:26.000
That's one way it can happen.

01:21:26.000 --> 01:21:39.000
Now, another way it could happen is what if you had maybe a section of a fairly large city with a very large and active movement.

01:21:39.000 --> 01:21:45.000
And they said, we just want to create a participatory economy in our section of the city.

01:21:45.000 --> 01:21:58.000
And what gives me this idea that I was in Greece for a conference at the sort of the height of the Syriza sort of power.

01:21:58.000 --> 01:22:05.000
And I was staying in a hotel and the conference was being held in a city that basically was in leftist hands.

01:22:05.000 --> 01:22:09.000
There was a whole section of Athens that was in.

01:22:09.000 --> 01:22:17.000
And people had asked me, well, why couldn't we just do a participatory economy, you know, in our part of the city?

01:22:17.000 --> 01:22:26.000
And my original answer was, oh, I mean, no, the whole thing only works if it's the whole if it's a national economy.

01:22:26.000 --> 01:22:29.000
And then I realized, well, wait a minute.

01:22:29.000 --> 01:22:38.000
We actually have a proposal for how it is that a small participatory economy would interact with.

01:22:38.000 --> 01:22:44.000
Countries through trade and everything that, you know, that have capitalist economies.

01:22:44.000 --> 01:22:53.000
Why couldn't this section of Athens basically organize itself with workers councils and consumer councils and do all this wonderful thing?

01:22:53.000 --> 01:23:01.000
Now, a lot of what a lot of what they need to buy and a lot of what they need to sell is with outsiders.

01:23:01.000 --> 01:23:05.000
But that's no different than a small country.

01:23:05.000 --> 01:23:14.000
Has to deal through trade or even international financial investment, you know, with other countries.

01:23:14.000 --> 01:23:27.000
My original reaction was would like nothing better than it's a viable strategy to say here we believe that we're going to start it and then we'll get experience.

01:23:27.000 --> 01:23:31.000
People will see that it works.

01:23:31.000 --> 01:23:34.000
My original reaction is it just doesn't work that way.

01:23:34.000 --> 01:23:47.000
That's, you know, that you have to somehow have a strategy where you're going to be, you know, you're the majority of the country wants to do it and reorganize the national economy that way.

01:23:47.000 --> 01:24:00.000
I'm not now. I'm not so sure that now I'm not so sure that it has to be some country where a political movement comes to power that wants to try it.

01:24:00.000 --> 01:24:05.000
I'm not sure that it couldn't be.

01:24:05.000 --> 01:24:13.000
I mean, in Athens, there were probably 50,000 people who lived in that section of Athens.

01:24:13.000 --> 01:24:25.000
I think it probably would be possible for 50,000 people, you know, in a city like Athens to say we want to actually run the economy in this part of the city this way.

01:24:25.000 --> 01:24:34.000
And we even know how to interact in terms of trade with other parts of the city, other parts of Greece that we know aren't running this way.

01:24:34.000 --> 01:24:39.000
And does it have to be a geographical unit?

01:24:39.000 --> 01:24:44.000
So, I mean, there are cooperatives all over the world.

01:24:44.000 --> 01:24:58.000
There are information and communication technologies that absolutely hold the potential to kind of mediate between those.

01:24:58.000 --> 01:25:20.000
And so one might think another possibility could be to have some kind of parallel system that is not defined through a specific geography, a specific place where people would have to where everybody would have to agree that this is the way to go.

01:25:20.000 --> 01:25:31.000
But that there could be, as I said, some kind of parallel system that defines itself through the people who already want to participate in such an experiment.

01:25:31.000 --> 01:25:42.000
That's an interesting idea. In the Internet era, I think that that is a possibility that would never have occurred to me in the past.

01:25:42.000 --> 01:25:46.000
But they can't, but not with a cryptocurrency, please.

01:25:46.000 --> 01:25:51.000
OK, just don't go to the don't don't go to a cryptocurrency on me.

01:25:51.000 --> 01:25:56.000
I get a rash as soon as somebody says cryptocurrency.

01:25:56.000 --> 01:26:06.000
There's one way that you can connect up that I do believe has not been taken advantage of to the extent that it should be.

01:26:06.000 --> 01:26:09.000
There is an international cooperative movement.

01:26:09.000 --> 01:26:15.000
It's been around for hundreds of years now.

01:26:15.000 --> 01:26:23.000
And the international cooperative movement, one of its principles is that co-ops should help other co-ops.

01:26:23.000 --> 01:26:37.000
And the form in which that's taken has basically been, well, a well established, long established co-op that's basically on pretty firm financial ground.

01:26:37.000 --> 01:26:40.000
Maybe it should, you know, it has an obligation.

01:26:40.000 --> 01:26:50.000
It has a duty as sort of a member of the international cooperative movement to establish advice for people trying to start up a new co-op.

01:26:50.000 --> 01:26:58.000
You know, we've got experience, we've got advice or even establish some sort of, you know, financial aid, you know, help give them startup money.

01:26:58.000 --> 01:27:01.000
That's been around for a long time and it's good.

01:27:02.000 --> 01:27:11.000
And I published an article in the Eastern Economic Journal, probably about 10 years ago, saying, you know, we could take that a further step.

01:27:11.000 --> 01:27:23.000
And it's very similar to what you're talking about, because these co-ops are not even in the same country.

01:27:23.000 --> 01:27:32.000
You know, who are members of this international association and who do engage in this solidaristic type of behavior.

01:27:32.000 --> 01:27:36.000
Why don't they when trading between them?

01:27:36.000 --> 01:27:44.000
But what they do is they all trade to the extent that they trade amongst themselves.

01:27:44.000 --> 01:27:48.000
They trade through markets.

01:27:48.000 --> 01:27:54.000
And we know that's actually not a good way to do it.

01:27:54.000 --> 01:28:07.000
So why couldn't they agree to trade amongst themselves in a way that is essentially.

01:28:07.000 --> 01:28:17.000
Giving the majority of the efficiency gained from the trade to the weaker of the co-ops.

01:28:17.000 --> 01:28:24.000
Now, in order to do that, you have to have some way of sort of empirically establishing what are the weaker of the co-ops.

01:28:24.000 --> 01:28:37.000
But I wrote an article in the Eastern Economic Journal saying, you know, I think that the international cooperative movement could take a further step in a direction that they've always shown themselves inclined to want to go.

01:28:37.000 --> 01:28:47.000
And this would actually be materially far more advantageous to the new co-ops and the weaker co-ops.

01:28:47.000 --> 01:28:52.000
So just from the point of view of, are you going to grow your movement more successfully?

01:28:52.000 --> 01:28:55.000
I think I can recommend it on those grounds.

01:28:55.000 --> 01:28:59.000
And does it take you in the direction of.

01:28:59.000 --> 01:29:01.000
That is the problem.

01:29:01.000 --> 01:29:08.000
Most people who work in the co-ops don't see anything wrong with markets.

01:29:08.000 --> 01:29:15.000
So it's a hard sell because what I want to sell them is you never really like market exchange.

01:29:15.000 --> 01:29:17.000
You always wanted to do.

01:29:17.000 --> 01:29:21.000
You always would have rather have done it another way, but you never had the opportunity.

01:29:21.000 --> 01:29:28.000
But amongst yourselves, amongst yourselves, you can create the opportunity.

01:29:28.000 --> 01:29:34.000
But that would require you to have already come to the conclusion that part of the problem is markets.

01:29:34.000 --> 01:29:43.000
And part of what prevents us from achieving our cooperative goal is that we unfortunately have to operate in the markets.

01:29:44.000 --> 01:29:50.000
Because what I was proposing is I can pose a way for you to get out at least amongst your interrelations.

01:29:50.000 --> 01:29:59.000
I can I can free you from the sort of market exchange process that is always problematic for you.

01:29:59.000 --> 01:30:04.000
If you don't think it's problematic, then the idea isn't that interesting.

01:30:04.000 --> 01:30:10.000
But I think it's very in some ways, it's similar to what you were talking about, which is.

