01:47:52.000 --> 01:47:56.000
What is the connection between Paracon and neoclassical economics?

01:47:56.000 --> 01:48:03.000
And why do you use some of these ideas and types of modeling?

01:48:03.000 --> 01:48:09.000
Okay, I'm going to say a couple of things that sort of get at this.

01:48:09.000 --> 01:48:38.000
Most people interpret when neoclassical economists model individual behavior as utility maximizing, most people interpret this as and most neoclassical economists themselves think of this as the only reasonable approximation we can make in theory to how people will behave.

01:48:38.000 --> 01:48:59.000
That people have priorities and preferences and what they try to do is maximize their satisfaction, their enjoyment, given their preferences and given the opportunities available to them.

01:48:59.000 --> 01:49:19.000
So most mainstream economists defend the use of the models of utility maximization as our best approach theoretically to predicting human behavior.

01:49:19.000 --> 01:49:33.000
Now, if you then go and challenge a neoclassical economist and say, do you really think that that's a good predictor of people's behavior?

01:49:33.000 --> 01:49:39.000
What the smart ones will say is, no.

01:49:39.000 --> 01:49:43.000
Sometimes people don't behave that way.

01:49:43.000 --> 01:49:49.000
They don't behave in their own self-interest, but that's the best we can do.

01:49:49.000 --> 01:49:58.000
If we're trying to explain behavior and we start with the assumption that the behavior is irrational, well then we're not going to be able to explain it.

01:49:58.000 --> 01:50:04.000
Now that's what a mainstream economist, I'm giving you the mainstream economist mindset.

01:50:04.000 --> 01:50:07.000
Here's how my mindset differs from that.

01:50:07.000 --> 01:50:11.000
First of all, I completely agree.

01:50:11.000 --> 01:50:15.000
Sometimes people behave in their own self-interest and sometimes they don't.

01:50:15.000 --> 01:50:19.000
I'm not interested in predicting how people will behave.

01:50:19.000 --> 01:50:25.000
I'm interested in evaluating economic institutions.

01:50:25.000 --> 01:50:40.000
So whether or not we can predict people, how good a job we can do in predicting how people behave by assuming that they will act in their rational self-interest given their preferences.

01:50:40.000 --> 01:50:45.000
I'm not interested in that.

01:50:45.000 --> 01:50:53.000
The answer might be we'll do a pretty good job of predicting behavior or it might be we'll do a pretty bad job of predicting behavior.

01:50:53.000 --> 01:51:02.000
Certainly for some people we'll do a better job of predicting their behavior and for other people we'll do a terrible job of predicting their behavior if we do that.

01:51:02.000 --> 01:51:06.000
But my job is not to predict people's behavior.

01:51:06.000 --> 01:51:11.000
My job is to evaluate economic institutions.

01:51:11.000 --> 01:51:22.000
And what economic institutions is, they promote some kinds of behavior and they discourage other kinds of behavior.

01:51:22.000 --> 01:51:34.000
So if I'm going to evaluate an economic institution from the perspective of what kind of behavior does it promote, what kind of behavior does it discourage?

01:51:34.000 --> 01:51:47.000
The only way I know how to answer that is what kind of behavior does the economic institution make rational for people to engage in?

01:51:47.000 --> 01:51:53.000
So that's why I assume that people will behave rationally.

01:51:53.000 --> 01:51:57.000
Not because I think they'll behave rationally.

01:51:57.000 --> 01:52:13.000
But because the way that any social institution encourages some kinds of behavior and discourages other kinds of behavior is it encourages the behavior that it would be individually rational for people to engage in.

01:52:13.000 --> 01:52:21.000
And it discourages or penalizes the behavior that would be irrational for people to engage in.

01:52:21.000 --> 01:52:24.000
Now let me say one other thing.

01:52:24.000 --> 01:52:31.000
So my goal is to evaluate the predictable effects of economic institutions.

01:52:31.000 --> 01:52:36.000
Does it promote people, does it encourage people to behave in solidarity with one another?

01:52:36.000 --> 01:52:41.000
Or does it discourage people from behaving in solidarity with one another?

01:52:41.000 --> 01:53:02.000
I mean in the case of public goods, does it provide incentives for people to consume too little, choose to consume what we can demonstrably demonstrate is too little public goods?

01:53:02.000 --> 01:53:12.000
So markets basically promote behavior because it's individually rational for everybody to demand too few public goods.

01:53:12.000 --> 01:53:20.000
And therefore we will get an inefficient amount of public goods in market economies unless we have some other procedure for deciding how much there's going to be.

01:53:20.000 --> 01:53:23.000
I'll give an example from centrally planning.

01:53:23.000 --> 01:53:38.000
I think that the institution of central planning discourages people from trying to seek self-managed work opportunities.

01:53:38.000 --> 01:53:49.000
It basically penalizes you if you try and seek that and it rewards you for not deciding you don't care.

01:53:49.000 --> 01:53:56.000
So those are the reasons that I use what I constantly get criticizing for decades now.

01:53:56.000 --> 01:54:13.000
I am criticized by many of my leftist colleagues as Robin you're always engaging in individualistic methodologies that are neoclassical.

01:54:13.000 --> 01:54:22.000
I'm saying there's a certain part of what they do that's useful for us.

01:54:22.000 --> 01:54:25.000
They misplay it.

01:54:25.000 --> 01:54:36.000
They use it to answer a question that's actually rather boring, which is how much will people behave in their own self-interest and how much will they actually not?

01:54:36.000 --> 01:54:38.000
And I already know the answer to that question.

01:54:38.000 --> 01:54:43.000
The answer is sometimes they will, sometimes they won't, some people more, some people less.

01:54:43.000 --> 01:54:46.000
There's nothing less that's interesting about that.

01:54:46.000 --> 01:55:01.000
But if you want to know what kind of behavior an institution is going to promote, the only way to answer that is what kind of behavior would it make it rational for people to engage in and what kind of behavior would it make it irrational for people to behave in?

01:55:01.000 --> 01:55:08.000
And I'm interested in judging institutions, not judging people in terms of how they behave or don't behave.

01:55:08.000 --> 01:55:25.000
So now there's one other thing I'll add, and that is mainstream economists tell us we should just take we should just take people's preferences as given.

01:55:25.000 --> 01:55:35.000
And this goes back to Jeremy Bentham, and it's sort of ours is not to reason why somebody likes something.

01:55:35.000 --> 01:55:42.000
The job of an economist is to sort of you like what you like, you don't like what you don't like.

01:55:42.000 --> 01:55:45.000
I do not stand in judgment of you.

01:55:45.000 --> 01:55:51.000
I'm just supposed to be telling you whether we can give you whatever it is you want.

01:55:51.000 --> 01:55:54.000
Are we doing a good job of helping you get it?

01:55:54.000 --> 01:55:58.000
And neoclassical economists have taken that lesson.

01:55:58.000 --> 01:56:04.000
I would say, you know, it's almost the bedrock that they stand on.

01:56:04.000 --> 01:56:07.000
It's their Bible.

01:56:07.000 --> 01:56:12.000
And there is something good to that Bible.

01:56:12.000 --> 01:56:26.000
For instance, if the alternative is that Joseph Stalin is going to decide what the Russian people want, well, then I'd much rather go with Jeremy Bentham on that,

01:56:26.000 --> 01:56:30.000
which is the Russian people want whatever they want.

01:56:30.000 --> 01:56:33.000
Do not sit in judgment on that.

01:56:33.000 --> 01:56:41.000
Do not say I, the revolutionary philosopher king, know better what people want than they know themselves.

01:56:41.000 --> 01:56:52.000
So in that regard, you know, I think the tendency of the economics profession, you know, to abandon the whole notion

01:56:52.000 --> 01:57:01.000
that there's somebody else who knows better what people should, what there's somebody else who knows better than people themselves

01:57:01.000 --> 01:57:07.000
what it is that they should have and they should want and what will make them happy.

01:57:07.000 --> 01:57:09.000
We really need to abandon that.

01:57:09.000 --> 01:57:13.000
That should go into the dustbin of history.

01:57:13.000 --> 01:57:22.000
However, isn't it obvious that people's preferences change over time?

01:57:22.000 --> 01:57:31.000
And do you really think that people's preferences change over time randomly?

01:57:31.000 --> 01:57:34.000
Here's what I think happens.

01:57:34.000 --> 01:57:40.000
At any point in time, people have certain preferences and they'll act on them.

01:57:40.000 --> 01:57:45.000
They'll act on them by choosing to work here and not there.

01:57:45.000 --> 01:57:50.000
They'll act on them by choosing to buy this and not that.

01:57:50.000 --> 01:58:03.000
Well, once they make those choices, today's preferences lead me to make choices.

01:58:03.000 --> 01:58:09.000
When I make those choices, I consume certain things and I do certain work and I don't do other work.

01:58:09.000 --> 01:58:19.000
Well, I have a model of human development that says you sort of start at birth, you have a genetic endowment,

01:58:19.000 --> 01:58:27.000
and then in large part what you become through life is dependent on what activities you've engaged in.

01:58:28.000 --> 01:58:35.000
So I'm going to engage in a whole bunch of activities over a 20-year time period.

01:58:35.000 --> 01:58:45.000
Isn't it predictable that whatever activities I engage in are going to have some effect on what preferences I come to have at the end of the 20 years?

01:58:45.000 --> 01:58:51.000
So here's the way I would put it.

01:58:51.000 --> 01:59:01.000
When we make choices today, we satisfy our preferences more or less,

01:59:01.000 --> 01:59:11.000
but we also, in some degree, sometimes we are transforming what I call our human characteristics.

01:59:11.000 --> 01:59:16.000
We develop human characteristics over time.

01:59:16.000 --> 01:59:21.000
And those human characteristics have an effect on our preferences.

01:59:21.000 --> 01:59:28.000
So this is what I call a model of endogenous preferences or preference formation.

01:59:28.000 --> 01:59:35.000
It says at any point in time, we have preferences based on whatever our human characteristics are.

01:59:35.000 --> 01:59:38.000
We make our choices.

01:59:38.000 --> 01:59:41.000
Two effects of the choices.

01:59:41.000 --> 01:59:46.000
Given our characteristics, our choices more or less satisfied our preferences today.

01:59:46.000 --> 01:59:53.000
But when we engage in the activity of those choices we've made,

01:59:53.000 --> 01:59:58.000
we modify over time what our characteristics happen to be.

01:59:58.000 --> 02:00:03.000
And when we have different characteristics two or three years down the road,

02:00:03.000 --> 02:00:10.000
then we'll probably have some different preferences based on those different characteristics.

02:00:10.000 --> 02:00:23.000
So one way I approach an economic institution is not only what behavior it makes rational for people to engage in,

02:00:23.000 --> 02:00:33.000
when they engage in that behavior, will it have a predictable effect on what kinds of human characteristics they develop

02:00:33.000 --> 02:00:36.000
and therefore what sort of preferences they'll have in the future.

02:00:36.000 --> 02:00:43.000
So let me go back to the question of central planning and worker apathy.

02:00:43.000 --> 02:00:46.000
So you put me in a centrally planned economy.

02:00:46.000 --> 02:00:56.000
I very quickly discover that having any sort of preference over what we're going to produce, how we're going to do it, is totally pointless.

02:00:56.000 --> 02:00:59.000
The institution discourages that.

02:00:59.000 --> 02:01:02.000
There's no reward for that.

02:01:02.000 --> 02:01:11.000
So I go ahead and I develop preferences that are rational in that context.

02:01:11.000 --> 02:01:17.000
I develop characteristics where I'm pretty apathetic about work.

02:01:17.000 --> 02:01:20.000
It was rational to do that.

02:01:20.000 --> 02:01:26.000
But it's part of understanding what the problem with central planning is that that'll be the predictable effect.

02:01:26.000 --> 02:01:36.000
So those are the ways in which I use what is highly criticized on the left as methodological individualism.

02:01:36.000 --> 02:01:41.000
I don't use it as a predictor of actual human behavior.

02:01:41.000 --> 02:01:46.000
Instead, I use it as a way to evaluate institutions.

02:01:46.000 --> 02:01:53.000
And I also think that it's important for us to ask the question.

02:01:53.000 --> 02:02:06.000
These institutions create certain biases in terms of how expensive certain things are going to be and how easy certain things are going to be to get.

02:02:06.000 --> 02:02:14.000
And those biases have a predictable effect on what sort of characteristics of people are going to develop over time.

02:02:14.000 --> 02:02:21.000
And I think that's even the most fundamental thing we want to ask ourselves about economic institutions.

02:02:21.000 --> 02:02:25.000
Economic institutions are going to create certain kinds of people.

02:02:25.000 --> 02:02:32.000
And in the end, we're going to have to sit there and ask ourselves, but were those the kinds of people we wanted to become?

02:02:32.000 --> 02:02:40.000
So that's that's my long-winded answer on this subject.

02:02:40.000 --> 02:02:45.000
My defense is mostly to feel aggrieved by my...

02:02:45.000 --> 02:02:51.000
I feel aggrieved that most of my fellow leftists, I think, falsely accuse me.

02:02:51.000 --> 02:02:54.000
Let me put it that way.

02:02:54.000 --> 02:03:01.000
